00:00:26.127 --> 00:00:28.710
DENNIS FREEMAN: Everybody would
like to believe that they just

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:31.279
simply sort of think about
the subject a little bit,

00:00:31.279 --> 00:00:32.320
and it will come to them.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:35.160
It's kind of like the
osmosis theory of learning.

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:37.350
But in fact, the way you
get good at something

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:38.550
is practicing.

00:00:38.550 --> 00:00:39.840
It's the same for music.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:40.980
It's the same for sports.

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:43.315
It's the same for academics.

00:00:43.315 --> 00:00:44.940
So the way you get
good in this subject

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:46.640
is to work on the homework.

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:50.650
We'll give two
kinds of homework.

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:53.320
There will be conventional
kinds of problems followed

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:56.680
by engineering design problems.

00:00:56.680 --> 00:00:58.110
The conventional
kinds of problems

00:00:58.110 --> 00:01:01.350
are intended to be
the kinds of problems

00:01:01.350 --> 00:01:08.390
that have simple, unambiguous,
easily checkable answers--

00:01:08.390 --> 00:01:15.860
so well-defined problem,
single, unambiguous answer,

00:01:15.860 --> 00:01:17.930
the kinds of problems that
you might be expecting

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:22.080
to see on an exam, for example.

00:01:22.080 --> 00:01:25.874
But then we'll also have
engineering design problems.

00:01:25.874 --> 00:01:27.540
Engineering design
problems are intended

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:31.710
to be a little more
ambitious, a little more

00:01:31.710 --> 00:01:38.690
fun, a little harder, perhaps,
perhaps not completely

00:01:38.690 --> 00:01:41.310
well-specified, sort of more
like the kind of a problem

00:01:41.310 --> 00:01:44.700
that your boss might give
you after you've graduated.

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:47.670
So part of the exercise
will be figuring out

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:51.240
exactly how to convince
somebody that you've

00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:53.260
got the right answer.

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:56.880
So those kinds of
problems are often--

00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:59.970
it will often be the case
that numerics will help you

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:02.600
in making an argument.

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:04.630
So it often will be
the case that we'll

00:02:04.630 --> 00:02:06.370
ask you to plot something.

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:09.880
Or maybe you just decide that a
plot is the most effective way

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:12.140
to communicate your result.

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:15.830
We are completely ambivalent
about what programming

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:17.750
language that you use.

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:21.170
Since 6.01 and 6.02
are prerequisites,

00:02:21.170 --> 00:02:23.120
we assume you all know Python.

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.780
So all the examples that
I give in lecture handouts

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:30.080
or in homework solutions
will be in Python.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.170
But if you'd rather use
Matlab, I just don't care.

00:02:33.170 --> 00:02:36.260
OK, we're completely ambivalent
about what programming language

00:02:36.260 --> 00:02:36.940
you use.

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:39.560
But it will be important
that in some of the problems

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:44.540
you'll find that useful
to be able to generate

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:48.200
a numerical kind of solution.

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.074
These are very different
kinds of problems.

00:02:50.074 --> 00:02:51.490
And to help you
with both of them,

00:02:51.490 --> 00:02:55.220
we have a different
idea about each.

00:02:55.220 --> 00:02:58.170
So to help you with the
conventional problems, the kind

00:02:58.170 --> 00:03:02.520
that have precise,
easy-to-check answers,

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:05.340
we've developed for the first
time ever over the summer

00:03:05.340 --> 00:03:09.450
a tutor-type
environment for 6.003.

00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:11.850
So this was intended to be
like the tutor environment

00:03:11.850 --> 00:03:13.500
that we use in 6.01.

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:16.147
It's one of the more
popular aspects of 6.01,

00:03:16.147 --> 00:03:17.730
the fact that you
can put in an answer

00:03:17.730 --> 00:03:20.460
and hit the button
that says Check.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:23.160
OK, so we're going
to have one of those.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:26.510
So the idea is going to be that
in the case that we ask you

00:03:26.510 --> 00:03:31.380
a simple question that
has a precise answer,

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.290
we'll use a tutor environment
to let you check your answer

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:36.480
to see if you got
the right answer.

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:38.610
In the case of the
engineering design problems,

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:39.570
that won't be the case.

00:03:39.570 --> 00:03:42.360
It will not be the case
that it's very easy at all

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:45.974
to think about a computer
program that would check you.

00:03:45.974 --> 00:03:47.890
So the alternative is
going to be that we will

00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:50.847
have extended office hours.

00:03:50.847 --> 00:03:53.180
So we're going to have something
that I think of as open

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:55.390
or block office hours.

00:03:55.390 --> 00:03:59.380
Monday and Tuesday
afternoon and early evening,

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:03.010
we've reserved the
basement of Stata, 32-044,

00:04:03.010 --> 00:04:06.250
for use of this class,
the idea being that that's

00:04:06.250 --> 00:04:07.750
a nice space you
can just come there

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:10.570
to work any time you want to

00:04:10.570 --> 00:04:14.720
hopefully because it's nice,
and hopefully because you all

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:18.310
know that there will be
other 6.003 people there,

00:04:18.310 --> 00:04:21.070
you'll just decide that's
a good place to work.

00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:23.680
And that's convenient because
in these engineering design

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:26.050
problems, if you run
into something that's

00:04:26.050 --> 00:04:27.970
unclear to you, we
don't really want

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:30.660
you to spend an hour pondering
what was being asked.

00:04:33.370 --> 00:04:36.950
So we want to make it
easy for you to get help.

00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:40.330
And you can get help from
peers, from other students who

00:04:40.330 --> 00:04:43.150
are there, but
we'll also make sure

00:04:43.150 --> 00:04:45.730
that there is at least one
6.003 staff member there all

00:04:45.730 --> 00:04:47.306
the time.

00:04:47.306 --> 00:04:50.390
OK, so the homeworks
will be due on Wednesday.

00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:53.930
That's the strategic value
of Mondays and Tuesdays.

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:58.150
So you can use that time
to get ready for turning

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:00.604
