00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:08.480
That

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:11.130
The abstraction that
we're going to use

00:12:11.130 --> 00:12:16.620
is we think about a
system as a thing that

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:19.610
has an input and an output.

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:24.100
Given the input and the system,
you can compute the output.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:27.430
Systems have one
input and one output.

00:12:27.430 --> 00:12:30.660
It's a very special
way of thinking

00:12:30.660 --> 00:12:36.670
about a system that turns out
to be surprisingly powerful.

00:12:36.670 --> 00:12:39.000
It's so powerful that that's
really the thing that we

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:40.280
will focus on in this class.

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:53.860
So it's the thing that I will
call the 6.003 abstraction.

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:57.610
That's going to be the
theme in everything we do,

00:12:57.610 --> 00:13:00.190
that representation.

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:02.020
And the best way to
get across, I think,

00:13:02.020 --> 00:13:04.180
how that's different from
other representations

00:13:04.180 --> 00:13:05.890
that you're already
quite familiar with

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:08.330
is to just look at an example.

00:13:08.330 --> 00:13:12.040
So here's a system that I'm
sure you all know all about.

00:13:12.040 --> 00:13:12.705
Right?

00:13:12.705 --> 00:13:14.080
This is not the
first time you've

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:15.204
seen this kind of a system.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:20.530
So you all know how to do this.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:22.945
Free-body diagrams,
F equals ma--

00:13:22.945 --> 00:13:25.120
there's an enormous
number of ways

00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:26.700
that you can analyze
such a system.

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:30.550
We're going to take a
very special approach

00:13:30.550 --> 00:13:34.340
where we think about
the system as having

00:13:34.340 --> 00:13:36.400
an input and an output.

