00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:44.400
We'll say a little more in
a minute about how arbitrary

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:46.180
it is.

00:13:46.180 --> 00:13:49.200
But the idea is going
to be that this system,

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:52.260
the mass-spring system,
the anvil with a spring,

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:56.060
there's an input, and
there's an output.

00:13:56.060 --> 00:13:58.810
So for example, for
some particular purpose,

00:13:58.810 --> 00:14:01.730
I might want to think
that the input is

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:05.070
the position of my hand.

00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:07.160
One reason I might want
to think about that is it

00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:09.120
is under my control.

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:10.890
So it might be
reasonable to think

00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:13.140
about my hand being the input.

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:16.350
So for example, my
hand can do this.

00:14:16.350 --> 00:14:17.390
Right?

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:20.600
So I might think about
the position of my hand

00:14:20.600 --> 00:14:22.670
being the input.

00:14:22.670 --> 00:14:26.410
So if I did that,
then what I could do

00:14:26.410 --> 00:14:30.325
is characterize the input
by some waveform, a signal.

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:37.330
In order to use the
abstraction, I also

00:14:37.330 --> 00:14:39.550
have to say what the output is.

00:14:39.550 --> 00:14:41.630
I might be interested,
for example,

00:14:41.630 --> 00:14:44.310
in knowing the
position of the mass.

00:14:44.310 --> 00:14:48.740
Then the output would be the
displacement of the mass.

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:51.990
That assignment of input and
output is somewhat arbitrary.

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:58.420
I get to choose that to
make the problem that I'm

00:14:58.420 --> 00:15:02.300
interested in as
easy as possible.

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:05.810
So for example, if I'm thinking
about this mass and spring

00:15:05.810 --> 00:15:09.770
system here, using
my hand as the input,

00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:11.690
that seems kind of
natural because that's

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:12.650
the thing I control.

00:15:12.650 --> 00:15:14.900
Thinking about the position
of the mass as the output,

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:17.690
that seems reasonable
because that's

00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:19.800
the thing you can
take a picture of.

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:23.110
It's the thing you can observe
from where you are now.

00:15:23.110 --> 00:15:24.640
But it's not unique.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:27.580
I might have wanted to
think about the force

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:32.010
that I'm putting into
it as in the input.

00:15:32.010 --> 00:15:34.830
I might have wanted to
think about the output being

00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:36.950
the acceleration of the mass.

00:15:36.950 --> 00:15:39.780
Maybe there's some limit
to how much acceleration

00:15:39.780 --> 00:15:43.190
some mass can take.

00:15:43.190 --> 00:15:47.270
So you get to choose the
input and the output.

00:15:47.270 --> 00:15:50.120
But you have to choose
an input and an output.

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:52.190
That's part of the abstraction.

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:53.420
And that's part of the power.

00:15:53.420 --> 00:15:56.570
We'll see later that part of
the power of doing it this way

00:15:56.570 --> 00:16:01.780
is that you draw attention
to the things of interest

00:16:01.780 --> 00:16:05.090
and push into the background the
parts that are not of interest,

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:05.920
at least not now.

00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:12.910
This kind of an abstraction
is an extremely versatile.

00:16:12.910 --> 00:16:17.000
Here's a completely
different kind of problem.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.120
Imagine water
flowing into a tank.

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:20.980
The tank is leaky,
so it flows out.

00:16:23.540 --> 00:16:25.027
There's a second tank.

00:16:25.027 --> 00:16:26.360
OK, what on earth could this be?

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:29.500
This could be--
maybe this is the--

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:30.660
it's appropriate today.

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:32.870
It's raining, or it was raining.

00:16:35.480 --> 00:16:36.500
It was pouring.

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:39.720
Rain When I came
in, it was pouring.

00:16:39.720 --> 00:16:46.770
Maybe this is nature
delivering rain.

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:50.390
This is the Woburn
reservoir from which

00:16:50.390 --> 00:16:52.929
we get water in Boston.

00:16:52.929 --> 00:16:54.970
Maybe this is the Fresh
Pond reservoir from which

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:57.630
we get water in Cambridge.

00:16:57.630 --> 00:17:00.900
Maybe this is the
rate at which water

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:05.940
goes from Woburn to Fresh Pond.

00:17:05.940 --> 00:17:08.730
Maybe this is the rate at
which water leaves Fresh Pond

00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:12.490
and goes into consumers' houses.

00:17:12.490 --> 00:17:15.460
The point is that
there's some abstraction.

00:17:15.460 --> 00:17:17.260
There's some
physical-- actually,

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:18.460
I didn't say that right.

00:17:18.460 --> 00:17:21.200
There's a physical thing--

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:26.660
rain, Woburn, Woburn reservoir,
Fresh Pond reservoir,

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:28.314
consumers' houses.

00:17:28.314 --> 00:17:29.480
There's some physical thing.

00:17:29.480 --> 00:17:32.180
There's some laws of
physics that dictate things.

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:37.040
But we ignore-- or ignore
is not quite the right way

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:38.150
to think about it.

00:17:38.150 --> 00:17:40.850
We think about those
rules of physics

00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:44.840
as rules that govern the
input-output relationship.

00:17:44.840 --> 00:17:48.440
So we think about then
the entire system.

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:51.950
Rather than thinking about it
as reservoirs and rain and water

00:17:51.950 --> 00:17:53.630
and flow and all
that sort of thing,

00:17:53.630 --> 00:17:59.780
we think about it as
there's a signal in, rain,

00:17:59.780 --> 00:18:03.830
and there's a signal
out, water usage.

00:18:03.830 --> 00:18:06.290
And we take all the
details of the system

00:18:06.290 --> 00:18:08.400
and bury it in this box.

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:09.480
It's an abstraction.

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:14.150
It's a way to suppress some
details to highlight others.

00:18:17.420 --> 00:18:21.710
OK, and we use this in a
huge variety of situations.

00:18:21.710 --> 00:18:24.820
We can think about a third
example here, our cell phone.

00:18:24.820 --> 00:18:28.070
Cell phone is an enormously
complicated system.

00:18:28.070 --> 00:18:30.470
But for the purpose of
understanding the input-output

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:35.720
characteristics, if what I
really want to know is how good

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:37.700
is the quality of the audio--

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:40.250
not that that's even a little
bit important for cell phones.

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:41.000
Right?

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.754
Cell phones are important for
texting and taking pictures

00:18:43.754 --> 00:18:45.170
and have nothing
to do with voice.

00:18:45.170 --> 00:18:47.960
But in the old days, cell
phones had to do with voice.

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:50.150
And I made this slide back
when that was still true.

00:18:50.150 --> 00:18:53.560
So I apologize it's out of date.

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:55.970
So here, the important thing
of the cell phone system

00:18:55.970 --> 00:18:59.540
was the sound in
and the sound out.

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:02.750
And the idea was to represent
the cell phone system

00:19:02.750 --> 00:19:07.300
by the transformation between
how the sound comes in

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:10.140
and how the sound comes out.

00:19:10.140 --> 00:19:13.170
OK, so we do this for an
enormous number of reasons.

00:19:13.170 --> 00:19:15.870
One is that it's
widely applicable.

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:18.680
You can do this kind of a
characterization for systems

00:19:18.680 --> 00:19:21.680
from electrical systems,
mechanical systems,

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:24.000
optical systems, acoustic
systems, biological systems,

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:29.250
financial systems,
all over the place.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:31.380
That means that this
kind of an approach

00:19:31.380 --> 00:19:33.920
is very powerful because
it's so widely applicable.

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:37.860
It also means that, for example,
every engineering discipline

00:19:37.860 --> 00:19:41.910
everywhere has some
course like this.

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:45.690
It's just too
powerful not to do it.

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:49.190
So regardless of what
department you were in,

00:19:49.190 --> 00:19:51.090
in the School of
Engineering, for example,

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:52.820
there is something like this.

00:19:56.740 --> 00:19:59.470
Another reason
this is interesting

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:03.070
is that it provides a layer
of abstraction that lets

00:20:03.070 --> 00:20:04.760
you focus on certain things.

00:20:04.760 --> 00:20:08.280
So for example, let's expand
on the cell phone network.

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:10.670
Imagine that sound
comes into a cell phone.

00:20:10.670 --> 00:20:15.990
Well, the job of the phone
is to communicate to a tower.

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:21.090
And that communication is via
some electromagnetic signal.

00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:25.200
Then the job of the tower is to
communicate with another tower.

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:27.629
That happens in
all kinds of ways.

00:20:27.629 --> 00:20:28.920
It could be a fiber optic link.

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:29.940
It could be a satellite link.

00:20:29.940 --> 00:20:31.170
It could be electromagnetism.

00:20:31.170 --> 00:20:33.040
It could be lots of
different things.

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:35.550
There's a lot of different
technologies for getting towers

00:20:35.550 --> 00:20:37.290
to talk to towers.

00:20:37.290 --> 00:20:39.630
Then towers talk
back to cell phones

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:42.780
via electromagnetic
signals just like these.

00:20:42.780 --> 00:20:47.340
And the cell phone eventually
generates an acoustical output.

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:51.000
The idea is that by thinking
about the signals and systems

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:56.580
approach, we have abstracted
away everything other

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:58.800
than the flow of information.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:02.780
It makes it easy to
concentrate, to follow

00:21:02.780 --> 00:21:07.170
the flow of information
through a complex system.

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:12.250
Because we have
pushed every element

00:21:12.250 --> 00:21:14.150
into the same framework--

00:21:14.150 --> 00:21:16.510
every element has an
input and an output--

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:21.610
regardless of the
underlying substrate,

00:21:21.610 --> 00:21:24.400
the analysis is similar.

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:27.250
That means that
components that are

00:21:27.250 --> 00:21:29.320
characterized using
this abstraction

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:32.320
are easily combined.

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:34.060
So we refer to this as--

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:37.330
we say that these systems
are combinational.

00:21:37.330 --> 00:21:40.000
Their combinational in
the same sense that Python

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.860
was combinational in 6.01.

00:21:42.860 --> 00:21:47.500
If you represent things
by Python functions,

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:52.850
it's very easy to combine the
functions to have a bigger

00:21:52.850 --> 00:21:57.150
function whose purpose and
details can be understood

00:21:57.150 --> 00:22:02.610
without knowing what was inside
every individual function.

00:22:02.610 --> 00:22:05.730
Similarly here, by knowing
the input behavior--

00:22:05.730 --> 00:22:07.290
the input-output
behavior of the cell

00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:10.590
phone, the input-output
behavior of the tower,

00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:12.270
the input-output
behavior of this tower,

00:22:12.270 --> 00:22:13.650
it's easy to compose then.

00:22:13.650 --> 00:22:16.680
And in fact, we'll spend a
fair amount of time thinking

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:18.472
through the rules
of combination.

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:28.430
So that's kind of an overview of
the most important thing we're

00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:31.310
going to talk about in this
class, which is the 6.003

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:33.860
abstraction, the
idea of representing

00:22:33.860 --> 00:22:38.050
a system by the
way it transforms

00:22:38.050 --> 00:22:42.520
an input into an output.

00:22:42.520 --> 00:22:44.520
So with that kind of
overview, what I want to do

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:49.140
next is say a little more
about what are signals

00:22:49.140 --> 00:22:50.610
and what are systems.

00:22:50.610 --> 00:22:53.010
It's the signals and
systems abstraction.

00:22:53.010 --> 00:22:56.010
We're going to need to know
some more details about what is

00:22:56.010 --> 00:23:01.190
a signal and what is a system.

00:23:01.190 --> 00:23:04.390
So basically, a signal is
just a mathematical function.

00:23:04.390 --> 00:23:08.407
In all the examples I
talked about so far,

00:23:08.407 --> 00:23:09.990
and in many of the
examples that we'll

00:23:09.990 --> 00:23:13.530
talk about throughout
the term, the function

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:16.630
is a function of time.

00:23:16.630 --> 00:23:19.730
And the signal can have
many different dimensions.

00:23:19.730 --> 00:23:23.620
So for example, the
mass-spring system

00:23:23.620 --> 00:23:25.520
evolved as a function of time.

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:27.520
The tank system, the
leaky tank system

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:29.420
evolved as a function of time.

00:23:29.420 --> 00:23:31.450
The cell phone system
had acoustic signals

00:23:31.450 --> 00:23:33.760
that were functions of time.

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:36.220
Time was the same in each case.

00:23:36.220 --> 00:23:40.780
But the dependent variable
can be a variety of things.

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:43.670
Here it was position.

00:23:43.670 --> 00:23:50.280
So here it was flow rates,
meter cubed per second of water.

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:55.900
Here it was perhaps pascals,
some unit of pressure

00:23:55.900 --> 00:23:59.260
to characterize the
acoustic waveform.

00:23:59.260 --> 00:24:05.210
So the point is that signals
are generally functions.

00:24:05.210 --> 00:24:09.260
We'll see that just like
functions in mathematics,

00:24:09.260 --> 00:24:12.147
there's a lot more to functions
than dependent variables

00:24:12.147 --> 00:24:13.230
and independent variables.

00:24:13.230 --> 00:24:15.104
And in fact, that's
going to be a key feature

00:24:15.104 --> 00:24:17.630
of our analysis of signals.

00:24:17.630 --> 00:24:18.470
But that's to come.

00:24:18.470 --> 00:24:22.760
So for the time being, the
simplest and complete model

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:25.910
for what a signal is is
it's just a function.

00:24:25.910 --> 00:24:28.940
The function doesn't have to
be a one-dimensional function.

00:24:28.940 --> 00:24:32.360
In fact, a lot of the
interesting applications

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:33.950
of signals and
systems is to look

00:24:33.950 --> 00:24:35.760
at multi-dimensioned functions.

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:39.020
So for example, my
research is in hearing.

00:24:39.020 --> 00:24:43.640
I'm interested to study
how do the cells respond

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:49.490
to sound so that we can
understand how broken ears work

00:24:49.490 --> 00:24:51.970
differently.

00:24:51.970 --> 00:24:54.190
When you have a hearing
deficit, like I do,

00:24:54.190 --> 00:24:56.680
when you have a
hearing deficit, what

00:24:56.680 --> 00:25:00.220
is the manifestation of that
at a signal-processing level?

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:02.440
How do the cells
respond differently

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:05.710
to people who have impaired
hearing from people

00:25:05.710 --> 00:25:08.500
who have normal hearing?

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:10.330
In order to study
that problem, we

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:16.650
take video pictures of the
cells at large magnifications

00:25:16.650 --> 00:25:21.740
and watch them wiggle
when sounds hit them.

00:25:21.740 --> 00:25:24.890
So that's a
picture-processing example.

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:30.200
So the signals, the independent
variable is not just time.

00:25:30.200 --> 00:25:31.190
It's a picture.

00:25:31.190 --> 00:25:34.174
So it might have x and y.

00:25:34.174 --> 00:25:36.340
In fact, the pictures we
take are three dimensional.

00:25:36.340 --> 00:25:38.537
So it has x, y, and z.

00:25:38.537 --> 00:25:40.620
And in fact, they're four
dimensional because they

00:25:40.620 --> 00:25:41.440
change with time.

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:46.750
We apply this kind
of a technique

00:25:46.750 --> 00:25:50.350
on 4D signals-- x, y, z, time.

00:25:50.350 --> 00:25:51.920
But it's still the property.

00:25:51.920 --> 00:25:54.940
It still has a property
that the signals of interest

00:25:54.940 --> 00:25:55.870
are functions.

00:26:00.540 --> 00:26:05.420
We will be especially
interested in this class

00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:10.550
in two distinct
representations of signals.

00:26:10.550 --> 00:26:13.030
We will call them CT
signals and DT signals.

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:14.280
CT is continuous time.

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:16.190
DT is discrete time.

00:26:16.190 --> 00:26:18.850
We're very interested in
that because we're engineers.

00:26:21.380 --> 00:26:27.170
A lot of physics lives
in continuous time.

00:26:27.170 --> 00:26:29.540
OK, the
mass-spring-dashpot system,

00:26:29.540 --> 00:26:33.670
the signals were
functions of time.

00:26:33.670 --> 00:26:37.375
Time was a continuously
varying independent variable.

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.710
So the leaky tank,
the cell phones, those

00:26:42.710 --> 00:26:48.650
were all systems whose
signals evolve in time.

00:26:48.650 --> 00:26:50.450
So they're all continuous.

00:26:50.450 --> 00:26:52.582
You can start with a
second and break it in half

00:26:52.582 --> 00:26:55.040
and get a half a second and a
half, and a half, and a half.

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:58.850
And there's no limit to how
many halves you can take.

00:26:58.850 --> 00:27:04.490
By contrast, a lot of the
systems that we will look at

00:27:04.490 --> 00:27:10.530
are things that evolve
in discrete time.

00:27:10.530 --> 00:27:12.500
What's your bank account?

00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:15.970
Well it only gets
computed once a day.

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:18.370
So it doesn't make sense to
talk about your bank account

00:27:18.370 --> 00:27:21.140
at 9 AM and 2 PM.

00:27:21.140 --> 00:27:23.140
Right?

00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:26.470
The bank updates your
account once a day.

00:27:26.470 --> 00:27:29.050
So it's something that
happens in discrete time.

00:27:29.050 --> 00:27:33.240
It's something that happens
in all computational systems.

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:36.030
So computational
systems generally

00:27:36.030 --> 00:27:42.950
operate on signals that are
functions of discrete time.

00:27:42.950 --> 00:27:46.520
What was the state at time zero?

00:27:46.520 --> 00:27:48.410
What was the state at time one?

00:27:48.410 --> 00:27:51.480
What was the state at time two?

00:27:51.480 --> 00:27:55.890
So the system is something that
eats a discrete time signal

00:27:55.890 --> 00:28:01.020
and generates a discrete
time output signal.

00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:03.120
And a unique part
of this class will

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:05.190
be converting between
the two representations.

00:28:05.190 --> 00:28:07.530
Because as engineers,
we often want

00:28:07.530 --> 00:28:12.150
to build something that
operates in the physical world--

00:28:12.150 --> 00:28:13.650
masses and springs
and reservoirs

00:28:13.650 --> 00:28:15.710
and that kind of stuff--

00:28:15.710 --> 00:28:19.430
and do the processing
computationally.

00:28:19.430 --> 00:28:23.080
Ever since the advent
of digital electronics,

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:24.980
it's just much easier.

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:27.740
Digital one, it's
just much easier

00:28:27.740 --> 00:28:33.120
to process signals in
the digital domain.

00:28:33.120 --> 00:28:35.630
So we will often
be interested in,

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:39.620
how do you represent
a signal who

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:42.350
naturally lives in
the physical world,

00:28:42.350 --> 00:28:44.150
and is therefore a part--

00:28:44.150 --> 00:28:48.470
whose signals are continuous
in nature, continuous time,

00:28:48.470 --> 00:28:50.720
how do you convert it into
a discrete representation

00:28:50.720 --> 00:28:53.130
so you can crunch
it on a computer?

00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:54.480
And in fact, how do you go back?

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:57.290
So for example, if
we were thinking

00:28:57.290 --> 00:29:00.200
about processing
audio signals, we

00:29:00.200 --> 00:29:01.910
might want to think
about how we would

00:29:01.910 --> 00:29:03.980
take a signal of
continuous time and turn it

00:29:03.980 --> 00:29:06.740
into a discrete
time representation.

00:29:06.740 --> 00:29:09.650
That's precisely what
we do when we want

00:29:09.650 --> 00:29:12.530
to record something in MP3.

00:29:12.530 --> 00:29:14.060
MP3 represents a sound.

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:15.500
A sound is something
that I think

00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:19.370
of as a signal in
continuous time.

00:29:19.370 --> 00:29:23.830
It's pascals as a
function of seconds.

00:29:23.830 --> 00:29:27.490
But we want to represent
it by a sequence of numbers

00:29:27.490 --> 00:29:30.340
because it's a sequence of
numbers that's easy to store,

00:29:30.340 --> 00:29:33.520
to communicate, et cetera.

00:29:33.520 --> 00:29:35.890
We do the same sort
of thing with images.

00:29:35.890 --> 00:29:39.580
The images of the ear that I
talked about in my research

00:29:39.580 --> 00:29:44.610
are things that I think about
happening at continuous space.

00:29:44.610 --> 00:29:46.920
Every time we look at a
smaller and smaller dimension,

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:49.410
we get a different
answer because the image

00:29:49.410 --> 00:29:53.030
has no quantization in space.

00:29:53.030 --> 00:29:54.470
But when I crunch
it, I don't want

00:29:54.470 --> 00:29:57.800
to work in something
in continuous space.

00:29:57.800 --> 00:30:02.950
I want to work in a sampled
version like a JPEG version.

00:30:02.950 --> 00:30:04.900
Similarly we want
to convert back.

00:30:04.900 --> 00:30:08.860
I mean it would be useless
for the case of the cell phone

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:10.750
to convert it into a
discrete representation

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:13.880
and then not be able to hear it.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:16.090
So we'll think about
the inverse process,

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:17.470
which is reconstruction.

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:19.930
If you had a discrete
representation of a signal,

00:30:19.930 --> 00:30:23.620
how would you turn it into
a continuous representation?

00:30:23.620 --> 00:30:27.240
And there's lots of ways people
do that here's a way that we

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:31.110
call zero-order hold
where you convert

00:30:31.110 --> 00:30:35.460
every sample into a
corresponding voltage

00:30:35.460 --> 00:30:38.910
and just hold that voltage until
the next sample comes along.

00:30:38.910 --> 00:30:41.100
This is the representation
that is most commonly

00:30:41.100 --> 00:30:42.225
used in things like MP3.

00:30:45.420 --> 00:30:49.320
By contrast, we might
do something cleverer.

00:30:49.320 --> 00:30:53.380
We might literally
extrapolate between samples.

00:30:53.380 --> 00:30:56.590
That is commonly done
in picture processing.

00:30:56.590 --> 00:30:58.960
The reason we use the
two different schemes is

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:00.580
that psychophysically,
the things that

00:31:00.580 --> 00:31:03.700
are important to your
eyes and the things that

00:31:03.700 --> 00:31:06.420
are important to your
ears are different.

00:31:06.420 --> 00:31:09.900
So you would hear
the errors more

00:31:09.900 --> 00:31:11.760
if you did the
linear interpolation.

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:15.280
And you would see
the errors more

00:31:15.280 --> 00:31:17.320
if you did the
other interpolation.

00:31:17.320 --> 00:31:19.945
And we'll do lots of examples
later on in the course

00:31:19.945 --> 00:31:21.070
so you see why that's true.

